<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-242-222 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 798 553</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Jan 15 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>When was U.S. shipping supercomputers to Hussein?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCormick, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SupercomputersIraqGovernment RegulationEthicsLegal IssuesInternational Trade.andO;Person:    Perot, H. Ross (Interviews).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>WHEN WAS U.S.andP;  SHIPPING SUPERCOMPUTERS TO HUSSEIN? 01/14/91 WASHINGTON, DC,U.S.A., 1991 JAN 14 (NB) -- On Friday evening's Larry King Live interviewshow, Texas millionaire H. Ross Perot charged that some branches of the U.S.andO;government had continued to encourage the export of a militarily significantsupercomputer to Iraq in August, after that country's invasion of Kuwait.andM;The revelation came when talk-show host Larry King took a phone call fromCommerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher who berated Mr. Perot for questioning theAdministration's policy in the Gulf.andP;  When Mr. Perot asked SecretaryMosbacher why the Commerce Department had pushed the export of asupercomputer to Iraq even after U.S.andP;  troops were on the ground in SaudiArabia, the Secretary attempted to avoid the question several times but neverclearly denied the charge.andM;The incident referred to by Mr. Perot involved the sale and shipment of asupercomputer to what the Texas businessman indicated was a known Iraqi frontbusiness in Brazil.andP;  Mr. Perot stated that such a computer could have beenused for nuclear weapons' development by the government of Iraq and that boththe Commerce and State Departments had continued to encourage the sale of thecomputer until finally blocked by the Central Intelligence Agency andDepartment of Defense.andM;Mr.andP;  Perot, founder of Dallas, Texas-based Electronic Data Systems Corp., wasstrongly supportive of the troops, a position perhaps to be expected sinceoutside of his battles with General Motors, which bought EDS and put Mr.andO;Perot on its board of directors, H. Ross Perot is best known for hissuccessful efforts to rescue his employees who had been taken hostage in theMideast as portrayed in Ken Follett's book, &quot;On Wings of Eagles.&quot;andM;A Texas-based newspaper editor who talked with Newsbytes expressed nosurprise that Mr. Perot was making a major effort to point outinconsistencies in U.S.andP;  government policies while offering his encouragementto those on the ground in Saudi Arabia.andP;  And the editor added that H. RossPerot is famous in Texas for showing up when people are in real trouble andholding out his hand to offer help.andM;(John McCormick/19910114)</TEXT></DOC>